default6.3.1 There is a demand-responsive service that operates here called 
defaultBwcabus
default. It is hailed by its architect as the answer to all rural transport problems. However, local experience shows it to be 
defaulta financial burden to the taxpayer, and to be operating in a most inefficient manner, which causes it to be unpopular. 
default6.3.2 The set-up of 
defaultBwcabus
default is too complicated. There are too many bodies involved: two local authorities, two regional transport consor
defaulttia, the Welsh Government, the University of Glamorgan, 
defaultTraveline
default 
defaultCymru
default and the European Union. 
default6.3.3 Freedom of information (FOI) requests have shown the cost of this 
defaultBwcabus
default scheme to be out of all proportion to the benefits for customers. Its own websi
defaultte purports to have a budget of £2.9million. It has been revealed by the FOI that massive sums have been put in from the various taxpayers’ purses, be it via local authority, Welsh Government or European funding, whilst only a small fraction has been forth
defaultcoming from the users. In 2012, the operator took just over £10,000 from customers, most of that amount from reimbursement of people’s bus passes.  In that same year, the University of Glamorgan was paid £91,187.86 in fees.  These figures merely illustrate
default the gross inadequacy of the system from a financial point of view. 
default6.3.4 The 
defaultBwcabus
default scheme is also mixed up with various scheduled services. These scheduled services can be accessed by anybody without previously booking; the rest has to be booked in adv
defaultance. The system is cumbersome and is set up in such a way as to have a high failure rate. As a consequence, these buses are seen sitting empty in lay-bys for many hours each day. 
default6.4 Most people in rural areas live in sizeable communities along major tra
defaultnsport corridors. These can be reached by normal scheduled services. Those that live in more remote parts would be better served by taxis; hence the need to make taxis part of the system as a whole.
