default7.1 What are the main challenges associated with fundingdefault rural public transport?default7.2 The Welsh Government has cut the subsidies on buses. The jury is still out how many services will be lost as a result. So far, users report loss of early and late services and loss of Sunday services. 
default7.3.1There are huge ineff
defaulticiencies in the current system. For example, most children get to school by bus in rural Wales. School buses are mostly used for transporting children to and from school. Consequently these vehicles only run in term times and are sitting idle most of the 
defaultday. Social services operate their own vehicles, often with just one or two customers on board. 
default7. 3.2 There needs to be a reappraisal of how such vehicles are deployed. There are some good examples of how this can be done. One local operator (Lloyds Coac
defaulthes from 
defaultMachynlleth
default) sells seats to the local authority to transport pupils instead of coaches. This works out much cheaper. Many of the pupils can be transported on scheduled services. The trouble has been with the lack of seatbelts. Again, Lloyds Coache
defaults has managed to overcome this issue by having seatbelts on all their vehicles. 
default&#xa0;
default8.1 Additional commentsdefault8.2 Competition between bus operators does not make for an efficient and cost effective service for passengers in rural areas. There simply is not eno
defaultugh patronage per mile covered. A different model is needed. Many people wish to see a repeal of the 1985 Transport Act so that government departments and local authorities can step in to sort out the current awful state of affairs. They wish to see reregu
defaultlation of the buses. 
default8.3 My experience is that certain private operators have a better grip on what works than local authorities and government officials. These operators know their customers. However, they don’t want to take risks with 
defaulteg
default evening service
defaults as they are clearly worried about the bottom line. The best private operators are medium sized ones (
defaulteg
default Lloyds Coaches as mentioned in par 7.3.2). Large countrywide operators have little incentive to provide a good service; their managements are too remo
defaultte.
default8.4.1 Franchising might be a way forward, offering whole regions for a certain number of years. Franchises would have to include a) research on customers’ needs including the vulnerable; b) the delivery of a minimum level of service to include early mo
defaultrning, late evening, Sunday, remote communities, etc; c) 
defaultaspirational
default growth of customer figures that would need to be achieved in order to avoid financial penalties; d) 
defaultaspirational
default service delivery standards including reliability and punctuality, deliver
defaulty of information, etc; e) 
defaultaspirational
default standards on quality of vehicles in use with clear dates for delivery of these 
defaulteg
default 
defaultall vehicles to be low floor, have seatbelts, have 
defaultwi-fi
default, etc. Again, for points do and e, financial penalties have to be stringent.
default8.
default4.2 Franchisees could offer a mix of vehicles and services from scheduled hourly services between major centres to demand-responsive and taxi services. One side of the business that is more profitable could offset the more costly side of the service. There
default are operators in Wales who could deliver such a package right now. 
default&#xa0;
default9 Conclusiondefault&#xa0;defaultThere are changes to rural bus services that could be delivered without any changes in the law although operators would find things easier if the law on competition does al
defaultter. As the law stands currently, passengers lose out. That surely was never the intention of the legislators. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe most important change needed is a change of culture. Bus passengers in rural areas need to be regarded as citizens with rights and not as e
defaultither expensive burdens who deserve only the crumbs nor as charity cases. Neither do we need to see the complete opposite as in the needlessly expensive and cumbersome 
defaultBwcabus
default project that is resulting in public finances being spent not on front-line servi
defaultces but on needless bureaucracy. 
